export const notes = "\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>1. Earth's Water Distribution</h2>\n  <p>Although water covers about 71% of Earth's surface, the vast majority is saltwater. Only a tiny fraction is accessible freshwater suitable for human use.</p>\n  <table class=\"compare-grid\" style=\"width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin-top:1em;\">\n    <thead><tr><th style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Category</th><th style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Percentage of All Water</th><th style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Notes</th></tr></thead>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Saltwater (oceans)</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">97.5%</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Too salty for drinking/irrigation without treatment</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Freshwater (total)</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">2.5\u20133%</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Includes all ice, groundwater, rivers, lakes</td></tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0.8em;\"><strong>Of that 2.5% freshwater:</strong></p>\n  <table class=\"compare-grid\" style=\"width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;\">\n    <thead><tr><th style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Freshwater Store</th><th style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">% of All Freshwater</th><th style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Accessibility</th></tr></thead>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Glaciers &amp; Ice Caps</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">68.7%</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Locked away \u2014 not easily accessible</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Groundwater</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">30.1%</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Accessible by wells, but can be over-extracted</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Surface water (lakes/rivers)</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">0.9%</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Most directly accessible, but very small amount</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Other (soil moisture, atmosphere)</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">0.3%</td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Mostly inaccessible</td></tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Key challenge:</strong> Only about 0.3% of all Earth's water is in rivers and lakes \u2014 the most accessible freshwater sources. This makes accessible freshwater incredibly scarce.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> Remember the key figures: 97.5% saltwater, 2.5% freshwater. Of freshwater: 68.7% glaciers, 30.1% groundwater, only 0.3% rivers/lakes.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>2. Human Uses of Water</h2>\n  <p>Water is used in three main sectors globally. Understanding each sector helps explain why demand is so high and rising.</p>\n  <table class=\"compare-grid\" style=\"width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin-top:1em;\">\n    <thead><tr><th style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Sector</th><th style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">% of Global Use</th><th style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Examples</th></tr></thead>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\"><strong>Agricultural</strong></td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\"><strong>72%</strong></td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Irrigation of crops, watering livestock, fishponds</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\"><strong>Domestic</strong></td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\"><strong>16%</strong></td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Drinking, cooking, washing, flushing toilets, bathing</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\"><strong>Industrial</strong></td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\"><strong>12%</strong></td><td style=\"border:1px solid #ccc;padding:6px;\">Cooling power stations, manufacturing, mining</td></tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Agricultural water use:</strong> It takes approximately 1,000 litres of water to produce 1 kg of wheat, and up to 15,000 litres to produce 1 kg of beef. As global population and meat consumption rise, agricultural water demand increases significantly.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Singapore:</strong> Average daily domestic water usage is approximately 130 litres per person per day. The national target is to reduce this to 130 litres by 2030 (down from ~153 litres in 2003). The global average ranges from 50\u2013300 litres per person per day depending on wealth and infrastructure.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> Agriculture (72%) is by far the largest user of freshwater globally \u2014 more than domestic and industrial combined. This is a common exam question.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>3. Demand-side Causes of Water Shortage</h2>\n  <p>Demand-side causes mean that human activities and population changes <em>increase the amount of water needed</em>.</p>\n  <div class=\"process-flow\">\n    <div class=\"process-step\">\n      <div class=\"step-num\">1</div>\n      <div><strong>Population Growth</strong> \u2014 World population has surpassed 8 billion. More people require more water for drinking, growing food, and industry. By 2050, the global population may reach nearly 10 billion.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\">\n      <div class=\"step-num\">2</div>\n      <div><strong>Urbanisation</strong> \u2014 People moving to cities demand more piped water, sanitation, and industrial production. Cities use significantly more water per capita than rural areas due to higher living standards and infrastructure needs.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\">\n      <div class=\"step-num\">3</div>\n      <div><strong>Affluence &amp; Development</strong> \u2014 Wealthier lifestyles use more water: longer showers, flushing toilets, car washing, filling swimming pools, and eating more meat. A meat-heavy diet uses far more water than a vegetarian diet.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\">\n      <div class=\"step-num\">4</div>\n      <div><strong>Agricultural Intensification</strong> \u2014 To feed growing populations, farmers irrigate more land and grow more crops, dramatically increasing water use. Irrigation accounts for about 70% of all freshwater withdrawals worldwide.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\">\n      <div class=\"step-num\">5</div>\n      <div><strong>Industrialisation</strong> \u2014 More factories and power plants require large amounts of water for cooling, processing, and cleaning. Developing countries industrialising rapidly (e.g., China, India) face sharply rising industrial water demand.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\">\n      <div class=\"step-num\">6</div>\n      <div><strong>Climate Change (demand link)</strong> \u2014 Higher temperatures increase evaporation and crop water needs, meaning farmers must irrigate more. Hotter conditions also raise domestic cooling and drinking water demand.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Example:</strong> In China, rapid industrialisation and urbanisation since the 1980s has led to severe water stress in northern cities like Beijing, where per capita water availability is lower than in many Middle Eastern countries.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>4. Supply-side Causes of Water Shortage</h2>\n  <p>Supply-side causes mean that <em>less water is available</em> \u2014 the amount of usable freshwater in a region is reduced by natural or human factors.</p>\n  <div class=\"process-flow\">\n    <div class=\"process-step\">\n      <div class=\"step-num\">1</div>\n      <div><strong>Variable/Unreliable Rainfall</strong> \u2014 Some regions naturally receive very little rainfall (e.g., Middle East, Sahel, Atacama Desert). Others receive rainfall in short intense seasons, with long dry periods. Climate change is making rainfall patterns more unpredictable.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\">\n      <div class=\"step-num\">2</div>\n      <div><strong>Seasonal Distribution (Monsoon Problem)</strong> \u2014 In monsoon climates (e.g., India, Southeast Asia), most rain falls in a few months. The rest of the year is dry, causing seasonal water shortage even in regions with adequate annual rainfall totals.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\">\n      <div class=\"step-num\">3</div>\n      <div><strong>Groundwater Depletion</strong> \u2014 Aquifers (underground water stores) are being pumped out faster than natural recharge (refilling by rainwater). Once depleted, aquifers can take hundreds to thousands of years to recover.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\">\n      <div class=\"step-num\">4</div>\n      <div><strong>Water Pollution</strong> \u2014 Industrial discharge, agricultural runoff (pesticides, fertilisers), and sewage contaminate rivers, lakes, and groundwater. Polluted water cannot be used without expensive treatment, effectively reducing supply.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"process-step\">\n      <div class=\"step-num\">5</div>\n      <div><strong>Physical Geography</strong> \u2014 Mountains, deserts, and landlocked locations can limit water availability. Poor nations may lack the infrastructure (dams, pipes, treatment plants) to capture and distribute available rainfall.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"case-study\">\n    <strong>Case Study \u2014 Sahel Region (Sub-Saharan Africa):</strong> The Sahel stretches across Africa south of the Sahara Desert. It experiences prolonged droughts linked to declining and unreliable rainfall. Desertification (land turning to desert) reduces the land's ability to retain moisture. Countries like Mali, Niger, and Chad face chronic water scarcity.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"case-study\">\n    <strong>Case Study \u2014 Aral Sea (Central Asia):</strong> Once the world's 4th largest lake, the Aral Sea has shrunk by over 90% since the 1960s. The Soviet government diverted the rivers feeding it (Amu Darya and Syr Darya) for cotton irrigation. This is one of the world's worst environmental disasters \u2014 a supply-side shortage caused by human diversion of water.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>5. Impacts of Water Shortage</h2>\n  <p>Water shortage has severe consequences across multiple dimensions of human life and the environment.</p>\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h3>Domestic/Social Impacts</h3>\n      <ul>\n        <li>No access to safe drinking water \u2192 waterborne diseases</li>\n        <li>Diarrhoea kills approximately 1.5 million children per year globally</li>\n        <li>Poor sanitation leads to cholera, typhoid outbreaks</li>\n        <li>Women and children spend hours daily collecting water (Mali: avg 6 km/day)</li>\n        <li>Girls miss school to fetch water, perpetuating poverty</li>\n        <li>Reduced food security and malnutrition</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h3>Economic Impacts</h3>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Reduced agricultural output \u2014 crop failures, livestock deaths</li>\n        <li>Food price rises and food insecurity</li>\n        <li>Industries unable to operate without water</li>\n        <li>Countries spend heavily on water imports or desalination</li>\n        <li>Lost productivity from water-collection time</li>\n        <li>Increased poverty in affected communities</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\" style=\"margin-top:1em;\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h3>Environmental Impacts</h3>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Aquifer depletion \u2014 land subsidence in some areas</li>\n        <li>Wetland and lake shrinkage (e.g., Aral Sea)</li>\n        <li>Reduced river flows harm aquatic ecosystems</li>\n        <li>Desertification and soil degradation</li>\n        <li>Loss of biodiversity in water-dependent habitats</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <h3>Political/Conflict Impacts</h3>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Water conflicts between nations sharing rivers</li>\n        <li>Mekong River: 6 countries dispute dam-building and diversion</li>\n        <li>Nile River: Ethiopia, Sudan, Egypt conflict over Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam</li>\n        <li>Mass migration from water-scarce regions</li>\n        <li>Political instability in severely affected states</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"case-study\">\n    <strong>Case Study \u2014 India:</strong> Over 50% of India's aquifers are overexploited. Farmers drill deeper wells at great expense; many small farmers cannot afford to do so and face ruin. States like Rajasthan and Punjab face critical groundwater depletion despite being major agricultural producers.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h2>6. Global Water Scarcity \u2014 Key Statistics &amp; Exam Strategy</h2>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>2.1 billion people</strong> (1 in 3 globally) lack access to safe drinking water. <em>(WHO/UNICEF, 2017)</em>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>4.5 billion people</strong> lack safely managed sanitation services globally.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>4 billion people</strong> experience severe water scarcity for at least one month per year.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>By 2050:</strong> Up to 5.7 billion people could face water scarcity due to population growth and climate change.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Most affected regions:</strong> Sub-Saharan Africa, Middle East, South Asia, Northern Africa, and parts of Central Asia. The Sahel region of Africa is among the most severely affected, with nations like Mali, Niger, and Chad facing chronic shortages.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Singapore's Vulnerability:</strong> Singapore has virtually no natural freshwater sources (no rivers, aquifers, or lakes large enough). It relies on its \"Four National Taps\": local catchment water, imported water from Malaysia, NEWater (recycled water), and desalinated water. Water is treated as a matter of national security.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Strategy \u2014 6-mark \"Explain\" Questions:</strong>\n    <ol>\n      <li><strong>State the cause/factor</strong> clearly</li>\n      <li><strong>Explain the mechanism</strong> \u2014 how does it lead to water shortage?</li>\n      <li><strong>Give an impact</strong> \u2014 what consequence follows?</li>\n      <li><strong>Provide a named example</strong> (country, region, case study)</li>\n      <li><strong>Evaluate/link</strong> \u2014 why is this significant or worse than other causes?</li>\n    </ol>\n    Use the PEEL or PEEL+ structure: Point \u2192 Evidence \u2192 Explain \u2192 Link.\n  </div>\n</div>\n";

